00:28:14.680 --> 00:28:15.840
to be a singer.

00:28:15.840 --> 00:28:18.810
I didn't know I could sing.

00:28:18.810 --> 00:28:22.100
So not knowing you
can sing comes first.

00:28:22.100 --> 00:28:23.750
Not wanting to
sing comes second,

00:28:23.750 --> 00:28:25.610
because I didn't
know I could sing.

00:28:25.610 --> 00:28:29.760
So here I was in the year
1990 in my high school.

00:28:29.760 --> 00:28:33.170
And suddenly these
seniors walk up,

00:28:33.170 --> 00:28:36.230
and I was whistling some tune.

00:28:36.230 --> 00:28:39.140
It was quite late in
the evening, about 5:30.

00:28:39.140 --> 00:28:41.940
And I was sipping on some
tea, and some of these seniors

00:28:41.940 --> 00:28:45.640
came up and said, hey,
you can whistle well.

00:28:45.640 --> 00:28:48.230
So I'm like, oh, OK.

00:28:48.230 --> 00:28:50.040
So you must sing.

00:28:50.040 --> 00:28:52.180
So I said, what's
the connection?

00:28:52.180 --> 00:28:54.160
A lot of people can whistle.

00:28:54.160 --> 00:28:57.320
So they said, no, no, no, you
whistle really well in tune.

00:28:57.320 --> 00:28:59.390
So it went on for
about five, 10 minutes,

00:28:59.390 --> 00:29:03.570
and then I was trying to
get out of that situation.

00:29:03.570 --> 00:29:06.847
So one guy caught
me and I said--

00:29:06.847 --> 00:29:07.930
I was trying to act tough.

00:29:07.930 --> 00:29:10.180
I said, hey, get
your hands off me.

00:29:10.180 --> 00:29:11.460
So the other guy caught me.

00:29:11.460 --> 00:29:13.085
So I was in that
situation, and I said,

00:29:13.085 --> 00:29:15.920
OK, I'm suddenly in a film,
and there are these two guys

00:29:15.920 --> 00:29:18.030
trying to hold two of my arms.

00:29:18.030 --> 00:29:19.920
And suddenly I
realized that, man,

00:29:19.920 --> 00:29:23.560
all the stuff that we see in the
movies is all-- is all a hoax.

00:29:23.560 --> 00:29:25.950
Suddenly when two people
catch your two arms,

00:29:25.950 --> 00:29:28.327
you're kind of-- you're
against the wall.

00:29:28.327 --> 00:29:30.160
So then I thought of
all the kung fu movies,

00:29:30.160 --> 00:29:32.810
and I said, OK, maybe
I should use my legs.

00:29:32.810 --> 00:29:34.530
And these guys
were tall and big.

00:29:34.530 --> 00:29:37.030
So I said, hey, OK,
let's cut to the chase.

00:29:37.030 --> 00:29:37.780
What do you want?

00:29:37.780 --> 00:29:39.050
I don't sing.

00:29:39.050 --> 00:29:40.710
I've never sung in my life.

00:29:40.710 --> 00:29:42.370
So they said, so sing.

00:29:42.370 --> 00:29:43.920
I said, look, do you want money?

00:29:43.920 --> 00:29:46.380
You guys are bullying me,
right, so what kind of bullying

00:29:46.380 --> 00:29:46.904
is this?

00:29:46.904 --> 00:29:47.820
You're not hitting me.

00:29:47.820 --> 00:29:48.810
You're not whacking me.

00:29:48.810 --> 00:29:53.372
You're not making me do a funny
thing, putting my pants down.

00:29:53.372 --> 00:29:54.580
I said, what ragging is this?

00:29:54.580 --> 00:29:55.496
What is this, singing?

00:29:55.496 --> 00:29:56.750
What punishment is that?

00:29:56.750 --> 00:29:58.580
But they were
incessantly after-- they

00:29:58.580 --> 00:30:00.929
were obsessed with the
fact that I should sing.

00:30:00.929 --> 00:30:02.470
So they made me
sing, and I said, OK,

00:30:02.470 --> 00:30:04.700
let's get this over with.

00:30:04.700 --> 00:30:06.436
And I sang.

00:30:06.436 --> 00:30:09.420
And more than them,
to my own surprise,

00:30:09.420 --> 00:30:12.400
I consciously sang for the first
time, and they all said, see?

00:30:12.400 --> 00:30:14.805
They were all giving each
other high and low fives.

00:30:14.805 --> 00:30:15.930
They said see, we told you.

00:30:15.930 --> 00:30:17.889
And they gave me a couple
of hits on my head,

00:30:17.889 --> 00:30:19.680
and they said, see, we
told you could sing.

00:30:19.680 --> 00:30:22.320
And I was like--
so I walked down--

00:30:22.320 --> 00:30:25.430
it was a long, lonely
road, walking down, taking

00:30:25.430 --> 00:30:27.850
the elevator, going
down to the canteen.

00:30:27.850 --> 00:30:30.320
And some of my friends met me
and said, hey, let's go home.

00:30:30.320 --> 00:30:31.890
And I said, yeah, OK.

00:30:31.890 --> 00:30:34.890
And then before
I went down, they

00:30:34.890 --> 00:30:37.130
took me to the cultural
secretary of the college

00:30:37.130 --> 00:30:39.630
and said, he's going to
be singing next week.

00:30:39.630 --> 00:30:43.190
So it was all in those
five 10, 15 minutes,

00:30:43.190 --> 00:30:47.590
my entire life just kind
of-- it was like something

00:30:47.590 --> 00:30:49.090
just opened up and,
plop, there was

00:30:49.090 --> 00:30:51.190
a portfolio that just
came in and said,

00:30:51.190 --> 00:30:52.770
OK, this is your road.

00:30:52.770 --> 00:30:56.650
VIKAS MARWAHA: This is great
that you opened up that time.

00:30:56.650 --> 00:30:59.780
I remember a similar thing
happening with me in college,

00:30:59.780 --> 00:31:04.369
where I had a stage fear, and
my batchmates were after me.

00:31:04.369 --> 00:31:05.660
We want you to sing in college.

00:31:05.660 --> 00:31:07.080
I was like, I've never sung.

00:31:07.080 --> 00:31:09.730
And they were like, it's not--
we just want you to sing.

00:31:09.730 --> 00:31:10.910
You can sing.

00:31:10.910 --> 00:31:13.150
And I did not sing at that time.

00:31:13.150 --> 00:31:14.744
I was scared.

00:31:14.744 --> 00:31:16.410
KUNAL GANJAWALA: I
didn't have a choice.

00:31:16.410 --> 00:31:18.014
I had four people
trying to beat me.

00:31:18.014 --> 00:31:19.180
VIKAS MARWAHA: That's great.

00:31:19.180 --> 00:31:21.680
That's great.

00:31:21.680 --> 00:31:26.380
If I had a chance, I would have
loved to hear your whistle.

00:31:26.380 --> 00:31:29.430
I know you sing so
well, but should maybe

00:31:29.430 --> 00:31:30.724
ask you sometime to whistle?

00:31:30.724 --> 00:31:33.140
KUNAL GANJAWALA: You've seen
the movie "Guzaarish," right?

00:31:33.140 --> 00:31:33.931
VIKAS MARWAHA: Yes.

00:31:33.931 --> 00:31:38.074
KUNAL GANJAWALA: So
that-- [WHISTLING]

00:31:38.074 --> 00:31:39.240
VIKAS MARWAHA: There you go.

00:31:39.240 --> 00:31:40.781
KUNAL GANJAWALA: So
that's on record.

00:31:40.781 --> 00:31:43.800
With the weather and jet
lag, my lips are pretty dry.

00:31:43.800 --> 00:31:46.740
I don't know if I
can do that today.

00:31:46.740 --> 00:31:48.017
But yeah.

00:31:48.017 --> 00:31:49.600
VIKAS MARWAHA: So
did you, after that,

00:31:49.600 --> 00:31:51.970
take any training in
singing, or you just

00:31:51.970 --> 00:31:54.330
went with the flow, just
practiced on your own?

00:31:54.330 --> 00:31:56.390
KUNAL GANJAWALA: No, I
rebelled against the fact

00:31:56.390 --> 00:31:59.690
that my parents encouraged me.

00:31:59.690 --> 00:32:02.950
They said, well, you continue
your studies, but how often--

00:32:02.950 --> 00:32:06.150
and this was
pre-private television.

00:32:06.150 --> 00:32:08.790
Private television
happened in '92.

00:32:08.790 --> 00:32:11.590
So this was 1990, and
my parents encouraged

00:32:11.590 --> 00:32:17.130
me, which is rare, because
at that time in India,

00:32:17.130 --> 00:32:19.520
everybody just wanted
to be a doctor,

00:32:19.520 --> 00:32:23.950
an engineer, the fixed--
but they encouraged me.

00:32:23.950 --> 00:32:26.990
They said, you must continue
your education, but you know,

00:32:26.990 --> 00:32:27.820
it's nice.

00:32:27.820 --> 00:32:28.430
You can sing.

00:32:28.430 --> 00:32:31.680
Why don't you pick up and learn?

00:32:31.680 --> 00:32:35.070
So I joined the
[INAUDIBLE] at that point.

00:32:35.070 --> 00:32:37.744
And I learned for about
seven or eight years.

00:32:37.744 --> 00:32:38.910
VIKAS MARWAHA: That's great.

00:32:38.910 --> 00:32:40.700
That's great.

00:32:40.700 --> 00:32:45.880
So you started singing jingles,
and I discovered that the doo

00:32:45.880 --> 00:32:49.560
doo jingle, that was one of
my favorite-- doo, doo, doo--

00:32:49.560 --> 00:32:50.830
that became really--

00:32:50.830 --> 00:32:52.199
KUNAL GANJAWALA: I can see.

00:32:52.199 --> 00:32:53.990
VIKAS MARWAHA: Yeah,
I drank a lot of milk.

00:32:53.990 --> 00:32:54.599
So--

00:32:54.599 --> 00:32:56.890
KUNAL GANJAWALA: [? Punjab ?]
and milk go hand in hand.

00:32:56.890 --> 00:33:00.820
VIKAS MARWAHA: [INAUDIBLE]
your ad, [NON-ENGLISH SPEECH],

00:33:00.820 --> 00:33:02.070
that also encouraged us.

00:33:02.070 --> 00:33:05.345
A lot of youngsters like,
[NON-ENGLISH SPEECH],

00:33:05.345 --> 00:33:06.640
you should drink milk.

00:33:06.640 --> 00:33:11.101
That ad was so-- it made
milk look very delicious.

00:33:11.101 --> 00:33:12.100
KUNAL GANJAWALA: It did.

00:33:12.100 --> 00:33:12.700
It did.

00:33:12.700 --> 00:33:15.370
VIKAS MARWAHA: How did
you become a part of that?

00:33:15.370 --> 00:33:17.190
KUNAL GANJAWALA:
There's a composer

00:33:17.190 --> 00:33:20.730
called Lesle Lewis,
who's part of Colonial

00:33:20.730 --> 00:33:26.200
Cousins with the great
Hariharan-- wonderful, great

00:33:26.200 --> 00:33:27.420
singer of India.

00:33:27.420 --> 00:33:32.580
So they-- Lesle gave
me my first jingle.

00:33:32.580 --> 00:33:37.060
So doo doo was the second
jingle of my life that I sang.

00:33:37.060 --> 00:33:39.590
And it was just, I
guess, the cosmos.

00:33:39.590 --> 00:33:42.560
And it was just God kind
of putting things together.

00:33:42.560 --> 00:33:44.380
And he gave me
that jingle, and I

00:33:44.380 --> 00:33:46.582
was jobless after
that for four years.

00:33:46.582 --> 00:33:47.790
And that was the only jingle.

00:33:47.790 --> 00:33:50.200
That was actually my
visiting card, so to say.

00:33:50.200 --> 00:33:54.290
But there are and
there have been

00:33:54.290 --> 00:33:58.870
so many other better singers
and busier singers in the city.

00:33:58.870 --> 00:34:00.930
So it always takes
time for someone new

00:34:00.930 --> 00:34:03.420
to kind of come in,
make their mark.

00:34:03.420 --> 00:34:08.380
Firstly, you need opportunities
to prove your prowess,

00:34:08.380 --> 00:34:09.909
if I may so call it.

00:34:09.909 --> 00:34:11.120
So it took time.

00:34:11.120 --> 00:34:18.739
But these are fine
arts, and so I held on.

00:34:18.739 --> 00:34:23.159
And I had my parents,
who supported me,

00:34:23.159 --> 00:34:30.880
because there wasn't really
the pressure to provide

00:34:30.880 --> 00:34:34.320
in the family, so that helped.

00:34:34.320 --> 00:34:38.730
But they really
gave me the support

00:34:38.730 --> 00:34:40.909
to go on and not give up music.

00:34:40.909 --> 00:34:43.850
And I really thank my parents,
because it's not too often

00:34:43.850 --> 00:34:46.780
that you have parents
that can support you

00:34:46.780 --> 00:34:55.250
in a nontraditional career
way back then, 26 years ago.

00:34:55.250 --> 00:34:56.429
VIKAS MARWAHA: That's great.

00:34:56.429 --> 00:35:00.130
So who was your singing idol
while you were growing up?

00:35:00.130 --> 00:35:10.720
Wow-- so many-- Lataji, Ashaji,
Rafi Sad, Kishore Kumar,

00:35:10.720 --> 00:35:17.330
MS Subbulakshmiji, Mandolin
Srinivasji as a musician--

00:35:17.330 --> 00:35:21.130
legend as a musician.

00:35:25.380 --> 00:35:27.170
And I've also been
influenced a lot

00:35:27.170 --> 00:35:32.570
by great bands and composers
and singers from the West,

00:35:32.570 --> 00:35:37.560
from America and from
the UK and Europe,

00:35:37.560 --> 00:35:44.180
so from Stevie Wonder to Ray
Charles, to the kind of stuff

00:35:44.180 --> 00:35:46.335
Quincy did, to Elvis.

00:35:49.060 --> 00:35:56.060
And then from Europe,
great bands-- Sting,

00:35:56.060 --> 00:36:03.400
U2, the Bee Gees, all the
legendary-- the Beatles,

00:36:03.400 --> 00:36:04.460
like I said.

00:36:04.460 --> 00:36:10.860
So phenomenal stuff, and great,
great artists, so all of them.

00:36:10.860 --> 00:36:17.660
I've never really looked upon
any one, because music is--

00:36:17.660 --> 00:36:23.130
the way I see music, it's beyond
boundaries and it's-- India is

00:36:23.130 --> 00:36:26.660
a melting pot of great music.

00:36:26.660 --> 00:36:27.450
So is the West.

00:36:27.450 --> 00:36:31.480
Because India brought the
whole concept of fusion music

00:36:31.480 --> 00:36:38.120
to the West as well, way back
in the '60s with Ravi Shankarji

00:36:38.120 --> 00:36:40.460
and Shakti, the group.

00:36:43.980 --> 00:36:46.540
VIKAS MARWAHA: So growing
up, was there an environment

00:36:46.540 --> 00:36:49.260
in your family with
music, like you used to--

00:36:49.260 --> 00:36:50.260
KUNAL GANJAWALA: No, no.

00:36:50.260 --> 00:36:53.000
My father plays the
harmonica, so that

00:36:53.000 --> 00:36:56.260
was the only musical influence.

00:36:56.260 --> 00:37:01.090
And he would play that whenever
we were traveling on a holiday.

00:37:01.090 --> 00:37:06.340
And he would play old
Indian songs, film songs.

00:37:06.340 --> 00:37:07.146
But that was it.

00:37:07.146 --> 00:37:08.270
And we were avid listeners.

00:37:08.270 --> 00:37:10.679
So radio was a very
big medium and very big

00:37:10.679 --> 00:37:12.720
influence, because we
didn't have internet radio,

00:37:12.720 --> 00:37:17.210
or there was no stuff like that.

00:37:17.210 --> 00:37:18.280
There was no internet.

00:37:18.280 --> 00:37:22.790
So yeah, no, as such, musical
influence from the family,

00:37:22.790 --> 00:37:25.810
besides my father
playing the harmonica.

00:37:25.810 --> 00:37:27.330
VIKAS MARWAHA:
That's great, sir.

00:37:27.330 --> 00:37:31.980
So how did you get your
first break in Bollywood?

00:37:31.980 --> 00:37:34.670
KUNAL GANJAWALA:
I'd like to thank--

00:37:34.670 --> 00:37:36.980
there was a very
senior musician,

00:37:36.980 --> 00:37:42.990
a female singer called
Poornima, who we all know.

00:37:42.990 --> 00:37:45.370
She was a child prodigy.

00:37:45.370 --> 00:37:48.680
She sang with Kishore
Kumar, Rafi Sad, Mukeshji,

00:37:48.680 --> 00:37:52.830
as a kid for-- Shankar
Jaikishanji, for RD Burman,

00:37:52.830 --> 00:37:54.850
for SD Burman.

00:37:54.850 --> 00:37:58.150
So she picked me up
from a college festival

00:37:58.150 --> 00:38:03.500
in '92, around the time-- and
that shift from me not wanting

00:38:03.500 --> 00:38:07.520
to do music and wanting to
take it up professionally

00:38:07.520 --> 00:38:09.680
came around '92, '93.

00:38:09.680 --> 00:38:11.750
So she picked me up,
and she introduced me

00:38:11.750 --> 00:38:17.660
to Ranjit Barot, who's a very
senior musician in the country.

00:38:17.660 --> 00:38:22.150
And Ranjit is a very, very
senior musician, singer,

00:38:22.150 --> 00:38:25.010
songwriter, producer, drummer.

00:38:25.010 --> 00:38:31.240
And Ranjit influenced me a lot.

00:38:31.240 --> 00:38:38.500
My career took off after
he endorsed me in Bombay.

00:38:38.500 --> 00:38:43.620
And so Ranjit is one
of the finest drummers

00:38:43.620 --> 00:38:44.750
that India has produced.

00:38:44.750 --> 00:38:47.230
And he has been drumming
for John McLaughlin

00:38:47.230 --> 00:38:53.620
for the last six or seven years,
so he's part of John's band.

00:38:53.620 --> 00:38:55.582
VIKAS MARWAHA: That's great.

00:38:55.582 --> 00:38:59.820
So recently, you have shifted
more into music composition,

00:38:59.820 --> 00:39:00.880
if that's correct.

00:39:00.880 --> 00:39:04.130
So can you tell us more
about your recent projects

00:39:04.130 --> 00:39:04.980
you're working on?

00:39:04.980 --> 00:39:05.896
KUNAL GANJAWALA: Yeah.

00:39:05.896 --> 00:39:08.160
I'm getting ready with
all the ammunition,

00:39:08.160 --> 00:39:15.400
because the whole model of
singers, composers, and lyric

00:39:15.400 --> 00:39:19.450
writers, these were very
designated departments

00:39:19.450 --> 00:39:23.300
in India from the time
film started in the '50s.

00:39:23.300 --> 00:39:25.810
So you had the
great Madan Mohanji,

00:39:25.810 --> 00:39:27.910
SD Burman, Shankar Jaikishan.

00:39:27.910 --> 00:39:30.220
You had [INAUDIBLE],
you had [INAUDIBLE].

00:39:30.220 --> 00:39:34.770
These were the great poets,
like you had [INAUDIBLE],

00:39:34.770 --> 00:39:36.546
and then you had [INAUDIBLE].

00:39:36.546 --> 00:39:39.180
So these with three
very important parts

00:39:39.180 --> 00:39:42.400
of a song, the process.

00:39:42.400 --> 00:39:48.140
Over the last decade, that has
changed, because what happens

00:39:48.140 --> 00:39:52.430
is inevitably, a song
is known by the singer.

00:39:52.430 --> 00:39:54.580
So you say, this is
a Kishore Kumar song.

00:39:54.580 --> 00:39:55.750
This is a Rafi Sad song.

00:39:55.750 --> 00:39:56.840
This is Lataji song.

00:39:56.840 --> 00:39:59.411
And that's how it is.

00:39:59.411 --> 00:40:01.160
There are very few who
realize that that's

00:40:01.160 --> 00:40:04.670
a a great song by Rafi which was
composed by SD Burman, written

00:40:04.670 --> 00:40:05.870
by [INAUDIBLE].

00:40:05.870 --> 00:40:13.570
That's only music enthusiasts,
because you have to go beyond.

00:40:13.570 --> 00:40:20.080
So that started kind of
affecting the composers,

00:40:20.080 --> 00:40:21.070
modern composers.

00:40:21.070 --> 00:40:24.150
They thought we were
taking away the shebang.

00:40:24.150 --> 00:40:27.910
We were taking away all the
limelight off that song.

00:40:27.910 --> 00:40:30.450
So what they
started doing, which

00:40:30.450 --> 00:40:33.130
is what record labels in
the West started doing too,

00:40:33.130 --> 00:40:34.561
which is taking away the--

00:40:34.561 --> 00:40:38.710
[PHONE RINGING]

00:40:38.710 --> 00:40:40.213
--which is taking away--

00:40:40.213 --> 00:40:42.380
[PHONE RINGING]

00:40:42.380 --> 00:40:47.900
--which is taking
away-- no, that's fine.

00:40:47.900 --> 00:40:52.000
Which is taking away the
power from an artist.

00:40:52.000 --> 00:40:53.600
Oh, this artist is
becoming very big.

00:40:53.600 --> 00:40:55.610
Let's clip their wings.

00:40:55.610 --> 00:40:56.880
So this was part of that.

00:40:56.880 --> 00:41:01.200
So the composers started saying
that, oh, this is my song.

00:41:01.200 --> 00:41:04.350
That singer sung it, and he's
making millions out of it.

00:41:04.350 --> 00:41:08.020
So the composers started
singing, which is fine.

00:41:08.020 --> 00:41:11.940
But don't diss any
part of the food chain,

00:41:11.940 --> 00:41:14.600
because we're not
doing this intently.

00:41:14.600 --> 00:41:16.950
We're singers, so we sing.

00:41:16.950 --> 00:41:18.810
Here's a great mandolin player.

00:41:18.810 --> 00:41:19.820
He plays the mandolin.

00:41:19.820 --> 00:41:22.140
This is a great piano player.

00:41:22.140 --> 00:41:22.932
He plays the piano.

00:41:22.932 --> 00:41:24.723
So we're just sticking
to what we're doing.

00:41:24.723 --> 00:41:25.620
So the model changed.

00:41:25.620 --> 00:41:28.700
So the singers was not
getting used as much

00:41:28.700 --> 00:41:31.630
as they were 10 years ago,
because the composers started

00:41:31.630 --> 00:41:34.660
singing, or the composers
started getting people they

00:41:34.660 --> 00:41:37.540
know who they could control.

00:41:37.540 --> 00:41:41.060
So it's a blessing, actually,
because every invention

00:41:41.060 --> 00:41:42.065
comes out of necessity.

00:41:44.680 --> 00:41:49.550
That made us-- being
kind of not as busy

00:41:49.550 --> 00:41:53.570
as we used to be till five
years ago made us look within

00:41:53.570 --> 00:41:56.847
and say, OK, so now I need to
write my songs and sing them,

00:41:56.847 --> 00:41:58.680
because the guys who
are composing the songs

00:41:58.680 --> 00:42:00.100
are singing them.

00:42:00.100 --> 00:42:03.670
So that shift had to
happen from within.

00:42:03.670 --> 00:42:06.490
And if we can interpret
composers' songs,

00:42:06.490 --> 00:42:10.076
then we can write our
songs, too, we thought.

00:42:10.076 --> 00:42:11.200
It can't happen every time.

00:42:11.200 --> 00:42:13.190
A great composer can
be a great singer.

00:42:13.190 --> 00:42:15.800
A great singer can be
a decent songwriter.

00:42:15.800 --> 00:42:16.950
But we're trying.

00:42:16.950 --> 00:42:18.170
So that's what we're trying.

00:42:18.170 --> 00:42:19.628
And that independence
is fantastic,

00:42:19.628 --> 00:42:23.690
because I did pray
to the god within.

00:42:23.690 --> 00:42:27.450
When I was a new kid on the
block, 12, 13 years ago,

00:42:27.450 --> 00:42:32.150
I said I don't want to depend
on anybody for my happiness.

00:42:32.150 --> 00:42:35.030
So I'm glad that I have
my little home studio

00:42:35.030 --> 00:42:37.954
and that I can write my
music and hit the road.

00:42:37.954 --> 00:42:39.120
VIKAS MARWAHA: That's great.

00:42:39.120 --> 00:42:39.661
That's great.

00:42:39.661 --> 00:42:42.350
So are there any recent
projects that are coming along?

00:42:42.350 --> 00:42:43.850
KUNAL GANJAWALA:
It's not that easy.

00:42:43.850 --> 00:42:48.010
I may be a big name,
so to say, as a singer,

00:42:48.010 --> 00:42:53.790
but I think I'm happy to do
independent music, which is not

00:42:53.790 --> 00:42:56.190
connected to films, because
when you have to do films,

00:42:56.190 --> 00:43:00.410
you have to be going back
and meeting the producers,

00:43:00.410 --> 00:43:02.450
and that's not a
road I want to take,

00:43:02.450 --> 00:43:05.980
because YouTube and independent
music is really big now.

00:43:05.980 --> 00:43:10.260
I just want to keep writing
good music, by God's grace,

00:43:10.260 --> 00:43:15.990
and want to collaborate
with great musicians who

00:43:15.990 --> 00:43:21.290
have traveled on this trip and
do some music which kind of

00:43:21.290 --> 00:43:23.971
makes me sleepless.

00:43:26.750 --> 00:43:27.950
VIKAS MARWAHA: That's great.

00:43:27.950 --> 00:43:30.560
So you have also
been really popular

00:43:30.560 --> 00:43:32.480
in the Kannada film industry.

00:43:32.480 --> 00:43:35.240
So are you focusing in that
space in in parallel, too?

00:43:35.240 --> 00:43:38.550
KUNAL GANJAWALA: I've sung
about 250 songs in Kannada.

00:43:38.550 --> 00:43:41.920
But what happens is the Kannada
industry feeds on the Bollywood

00:43:41.920 --> 00:43:43.960
industry.

00:43:43.960 --> 00:43:46.890
All the industries feed
on the Hindi industry.

00:43:46.890 --> 00:43:49.667
So automatically, all
my contemporaries,

00:43:49.667 --> 00:43:51.250
whether it's
[INAUDIBLE], whether it's

00:43:51.250 --> 00:43:54.530
Shaan, whether it's KK, whether
it's Mohit, who came after us,

00:43:54.530 --> 00:44:00.042
Mohit Chauhan, all of us-- the
quantity of work has gone down.

00:44:00.042 --> 00:44:01.500
But we have enough
of a repertoire.

00:44:01.500 --> 00:44:04.290
I've got about 1,200-plus songs,
including my Kannada songs

00:44:04.290 --> 00:44:07.420
and Bengali songs and Punjabi
songs and Hindi songs.

00:44:07.420 --> 00:44:10.210
So we have enough
for this lifetime

00:44:10.210 --> 00:44:12.590
to pass by without
really knocking

00:44:12.590 --> 00:44:14.990
on the doors of a
composer saying,

00:44:14.990 --> 00:44:17.140
can you give me a
couple of more songs?

00:44:17.140 --> 00:44:17.660
Let's party.

00:44:17.660 --> 00:44:18.750
Let's hang out.

00:44:18.750 --> 00:44:22.630
I can't hang out with people.

00:44:22.630 --> 00:44:25.150
There's got to be
dignity in work.

00:44:25.150 --> 00:44:27.830
And I'm old school.

00:44:27.830 --> 00:44:32.310
I'm sorry, I don't like to--
I let my profession speak.

00:44:32.310 --> 00:44:35.100
If I don't have the credentials
workwise, don't hire me.

00:44:35.100 --> 00:44:38.290
But I can't suck up to you.

00:44:38.290 --> 00:44:42.716
VIKAS MARWAHA: So did you learn
Kannada to sing Kannada songs?

00:44:42.716 --> 00:44:44.090
KUNAL GANJAWALA:
I can understand

00:44:44.090 --> 00:44:46.210
when people speak Kannada,
because every time I

00:44:46.210 --> 00:44:49.350
write a Kannada song or a Tamil
song or a Telugu song-- yeah,

00:44:49.350 --> 00:44:51.740
you heard Telugu, but I can't
sing Telugu, because this

00:44:51.740 --> 00:44:54.370
is Telugu land, Silicon Valley.

00:44:54.370 --> 00:44:57.750
So my brother-in-law,
my nephew, his father

00:44:57.750 --> 00:45:01.950
is Karnataka, so my sister
is married into Karnataka.

00:45:01.950 --> 00:45:04.350
But I can understand
conversational Kannada.

00:45:04.350 --> 00:45:05.430
I can't speak it.

00:45:05.430 --> 00:45:07.860
But I would write down--
I would break down

00:45:07.860 --> 00:45:11.190
every line-- in
every language that I

00:45:11.190 --> 00:45:12.950
sing in which I
don't understand,

00:45:12.950 --> 00:45:17.040
I would write down what
the line means word by word

00:45:17.040 --> 00:45:21.050
so that I could kind of
express what I'm singing.

00:45:21.050 --> 00:45:22.260
VIKAS MARWAHA: That's great.

00:45:22.260 --> 00:45:25.570
So I know you already
touched base on this,

00:45:25.570 --> 00:45:29.130
but you've been in
Bollywood music industry

00:45:29.130 --> 00:45:32.947
for more than a decade, and
you've seen a lot of changes.

00:45:32.947 --> 00:45:35.280
What do you feel about the
current music being produced?

00:45:35.280 --> 00:45:36.060
What are you hoping--

00:45:36.060 --> 00:45:38.226
KUNAL GANJAWALA: Some of
the music that's coming out

00:45:38.226 --> 00:45:39.200
is fabulous.

00:45:39.200 --> 00:45:41.380
There's a singer
called Arijit Singh,

00:45:41.380 --> 00:45:43.230
and I think he's phenomenal.

00:45:43.230 --> 00:45:48.631
He's a great gift to the lineage
of all the great singers,

00:45:48.631 --> 00:45:49.880
composers, that have happened.

00:45:49.880 --> 00:45:55.150
And I'm very happy that someone
good is singing, because he

00:45:55.150 --> 00:45:56.360
can sing in a lot of genres.

00:45:56.360 --> 00:46:00.170
He's a very potent singer,
very competent singer.

00:46:00.170 --> 00:46:01.760
He's got a great heart.

00:46:01.760 --> 00:46:03.100
He's got a great vibe.

00:46:03.100 --> 00:46:06.710
There's another singer
called Benny Dayal.

00:46:06.710 --> 00:46:09.440
Benny is wonderful, too.

00:46:09.440 --> 00:46:12.830
He sings the whole R&amp;B thing.

00:46:12.830 --> 00:46:14.630
That's his thing.

00:46:14.630 --> 00:46:17.580
He sings R&amp;B, essentially,
and he's wonderful.

00:46:17.580 --> 00:46:20.750
So these two singers
really, really-- I

00:46:20.750 --> 00:46:22.880
like listening to their music.

00:46:22.880 --> 00:46:25.770
So there is a good crop and
some very nice songwriters.

00:46:25.770 --> 00:46:27.890
There was a period till
about two years ago where

00:46:27.890 --> 00:46:30.010
melody was-- there's
another singer,

00:46:30.010 --> 00:46:32.392
a composer called
Jeet Ganguly, who's

00:46:32.392 --> 00:46:33.600
writing some fabulous melody.

00:46:33.600 --> 00:46:35.230
So melody is back.

00:46:35.230 --> 00:46:38.910
And if you don't have melody,
you can keep making noise.

00:46:38.910 --> 00:46:41.970
You can use all the gadgets,
possibly, that are available,

00:46:41.970 --> 00:46:44.000
and all technology, but
if there's no melody,

00:46:44.000 --> 00:46:46.390
there's nothing that can
hook you and hold you back.

00:46:46.390 --> 00:46:49.594
So it's a great time in
the Hindi films, as well.

00:46:49.594 --> 00:46:50.760
VIKAS MARWAHA: That's great.

00:46:50.760 --> 00:46:54.510
As [INAUDIBLE] said, we
had Benny Dayal and Arijit

00:46:54.510 --> 00:46:55.800
Singh for Talk at Google, too.

00:46:55.800 --> 00:46:59.016
I hosted Benny Dayal,
so that's great

00:46:59.016 --> 00:47:01.550
that you talked about them.

00:47:01.550 --> 00:47:05.150
So finally, sir, you're
performing tonight

00:47:05.150 --> 00:47:09.560
at ICC Milpitas for a very noble
cause you talked about earlier.

00:47:09.560 --> 00:47:13.980
So what songs can the
audience expect from you

00:47:13.980 --> 00:47:17.480
that will be joining you today?

00:47:17.480 --> 00:47:21.190
KUNAL GANJAWALA: I have
about 45 chart-toppers,

00:47:21.190 --> 00:47:24.420
so I can't do 45 chart-toppers
in 1 and 1/2 hours.

00:47:24.420 --> 00:47:31.510
But I'll do an amalgamation
of-- I'll club as much as I can.

00:47:31.510 --> 00:47:35.540
I'll do [INAUDIBLE], and
I'll do "Bheegey Hont."

00:47:35.540 --> 00:47:41.530
I'll do at least 20 of
my chart-toppers, some

00:47:41.530 --> 00:47:44.360
of them half, some of them
full, some of them as a medley.

00:47:44.360 --> 00:47:48.340
And hope you guys are
happy and satisfied.

00:47:48.340 --> 00:47:51.260
If you're not, I'll send
you my manager's number

00:47:51.260 --> 00:47:53.340
and we'll come back.

00:47:53.340 --> 00:47:57.905
But I'm honored to be sharing
the stage with Mandolin U.

00:47:57.905 --> 00:48:02.510
Rajeshji and
[? Harmit. ?] I think

00:48:02.510 --> 00:48:06.190
I'm very lucky to be on
the same stage as them,

00:48:06.190 --> 00:48:08.700
because I really,
honestly feel they

00:48:08.700 --> 00:48:11.970
bring so much more to my music.

00:48:11.970 --> 00:48:13.600
And it's a pleasure.

00:48:13.600 --> 00:48:16.250
It's been a couple of years
since we've known each other,

00:48:16.250 --> 00:48:17.779
and it's fabulous.

00:48:17.779 --> 00:48:19.320
I look forward to
today, because what

00:48:19.320 --> 00:48:22.050
I'm going to do today, before
I bring in the Bollywood set,

00:48:22.050 --> 00:48:24.890
I haven't done-- I haven't done.

00:48:24.890 --> 00:48:29.812
So we look forward to those
butterflies in my tummy.

00:48:29.812 --> 00:48:31.020
VIKAS MARWAHA: This is great.

00:48:31.020 --> 00:48:33.300
I also look forward to
your concert tonight.

00:48:33.300 --> 00:48:37.529
And now I'd like to open
the questions to Googlers

00:48:37.529 --> 00:48:39.445
that we have here, if
they have any questions.

00:48:44.710 --> 00:48:46.602
KUNAL GANJAWALA: No Googlese.

00:48:46.602 --> 00:48:48.310
AUDIENCE: Thank you
for coming here, sir.

00:48:50.890 --> 00:48:52.930
In the recent, let's
say, five or seven years

00:48:52.930 --> 00:48:54.940
there's been a big
trend in Bollywood music

00:48:54.940 --> 00:48:58.600
to use synthesizers and so on.

00:48:58.600 --> 00:49:00.690
Every time you see or
you listen to a song

00:49:00.690 --> 00:49:03.450
where they've used either
an orchestra or at least

00:49:03.450 --> 00:49:05.310
real, acoustic
instruments, it just

00:49:05.310 --> 00:49:06.780
sounds completely different.

00:49:06.780 --> 00:49:08.310
Why is this trend changing?

00:49:08.310 --> 00:49:09.980
Why aren't we still
doing pure music

00:49:09.980 --> 00:49:11.630
like we did in the old days?

00:49:14.290 --> 00:49:17.620
KUNAL GANJAWALA: We've always
looked towards the West.

00:49:17.620 --> 00:49:20.570
We've always looked at the
music that's happening in the US

00:49:20.570 --> 00:49:23.460
and in Europe and UK.

00:49:23.460 --> 00:49:24.915
So the trends are
changing there,

00:49:24.915 --> 00:49:31.250
and our pop music has
a style quotient, also.

00:49:31.250 --> 00:49:33.790
We've always looked at
the West, unfortunately.

00:49:33.790 --> 00:49:36.460
And that has caused--
because there's

00:49:36.460 --> 00:49:38.330
a lot of noise
happening even here.

00:49:38.330 --> 00:49:40.740
You have great artists who
are not cutting records,

00:49:40.740 --> 00:49:44.510
and you have a lot of
production, so to say,

00:49:44.510 --> 00:49:50.440
produced, like you said-- just
lots of gear, but no melody.

00:49:50.440 --> 00:49:53.150
There's lots of stuff
you hear-- and I

00:49:53.150 --> 00:49:54.720
don't mean to diss
any of the music,

00:49:54.720 --> 00:50:00.070
but you go back just 25
years or even 15 years

00:50:00.070 --> 00:50:02.190
and you still had melody.

00:50:02.190 --> 00:50:05.020
So we're like that.

00:50:05.020 --> 00:50:07.170
We always look and say,
ah, that's happening.

00:50:07.170 --> 00:50:11.210
We have great artists
like-- singers like Beyonce.

00:50:11.210 --> 00:50:14.349
She's a fabulous singer, but
her producers are not even

00:50:14.349 --> 00:50:16.640
writing stuff for her, which
she wrote in her first two

00:50:16.640 --> 00:50:19.210
albums, Destiny's Child.

00:50:19.210 --> 00:50:20.110
There were melodies.

00:50:20.110 --> 00:50:21.680
Even something that
she wrote seven,

00:50:21.680 --> 00:50:23.950
eight years ago,
still had melody.

00:50:23.950 --> 00:50:26.110
But that's all changing.

00:50:26.110 --> 00:50:29.020
And I think we as
consumers are to be blamed.

00:50:29.020 --> 00:50:31.320
So if more responsible
people like you

00:50:31.320 --> 00:50:36.620
start asking this question, stop
downloading music, paid music,

00:50:36.620 --> 00:50:38.720
I think they'll
get their answers

00:50:38.720 --> 00:50:41.430
and they'll start moving
and making a shift.

00:50:41.430 --> 00:50:46.197
So we need to not
consume crap musically.

00:50:46.197 --> 00:50:47.780
AUDIENCE: So as
someone who's creating

00:50:47.780 --> 00:50:49.154
stuff that people
are paying for,

00:50:49.154 --> 00:50:52.574
do you see a market for
pure or really [INAUDIBLE]?

00:50:52.574 --> 00:50:53.740
KUNAL GANJAWALA: Absolutely.

00:50:53.740 --> 00:50:58.440
See, India, even our pop music
two, three years ago was noisy.

00:50:58.440 --> 00:51:01.740
There was a shift, three
or four years of confusion,

00:51:01.740 --> 00:51:04.420
whether we should have it
more electronic or what.

00:51:04.420 --> 00:51:08.920
And suddenly, Jeet Ganguly
and Armaan Malik came in,

00:51:08.920 --> 00:51:10.900
and they've brought melody.

00:51:10.900 --> 00:51:13.160
So it's bound to happen.

00:51:13.160 --> 00:51:15.320
And also, unfortunately,
record labels

00:51:15.320 --> 00:51:17.930
control the artists too
much, and the songwriters.

00:51:17.930 --> 00:51:20.030
They think they know what
sells, because they just

00:51:20.030 --> 00:51:21.890
want to see the jacket.

00:51:21.890 --> 00:51:25.220
They just want to see money.

00:51:25.220 --> 00:51:27.870
And that's not going to change,
because every artist that

00:51:27.870 --> 00:51:30.030
starts rebelling
gets thrown away

00:51:30.030 --> 00:51:33.410
in the darkness,
like the greatest,

00:51:33.410 --> 00:51:36.840
like Michael Jackson or
George Michael, from modern,

00:51:36.840 --> 00:51:38.210
from current times.

00:51:38.210 --> 00:51:39.960
And that's why Stevie's
not writing albums

00:51:39.960 --> 00:51:41.670
after having written so many.

00:51:41.670 --> 00:51:44.460
He wrote his last album
about 10 years ago.

00:51:44.460 --> 00:51:48.770
So if you try to
fight the system,

00:51:48.770 --> 00:51:53.880
the system just throws you--
chews you and throws you.

00:51:53.880 --> 00:51:57.060
So it's upon consumption.

00:51:57.060 --> 00:51:59.360
So if there is no demand,
there will be no supply.

00:51:59.360 --> 00:52:01.660
So we have to
control the demand.

00:52:06.360 --> 00:52:07.047
Yes, please.

00:52:12.495 --> 00:52:13.370
AUDIENCE: Hello, sir.

00:52:13.370 --> 00:52:14.157
I'm [INAUDIBLE]

00:52:14.157 --> 00:52:14.990
KUNAL GANJAWALA: Hi.

00:52:14.990 --> 00:52:15.531
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:52:15.531 --> 00:52:16.738
I'm a big fan of yours.

00:52:20.330 --> 00:52:24.180
What industry you like--
Kollywood, Bollywood,

00:52:24.180 --> 00:52:27.042
or Dollywood, which
language, and which language

00:52:27.042 --> 00:52:27.750
you want to sing?

00:52:27.750 --> 00:52:30.450
KUNAL GANJAWALA: Actually,
I just love doing music,

00:52:30.450 --> 00:52:33.840
so language is something--
and we are lucky that India

00:52:33.840 --> 00:52:38.710
as a country, as small as
it is if you compare it

00:52:38.710 --> 00:52:40.650
to the continents
and the landmass,

00:52:40.650 --> 00:52:42.080
we have so many languages.

00:52:42.080 --> 00:52:46.470
So I'm just lucky that I was
born in a country with so much

00:52:46.470 --> 00:52:48.680
diversity and so much culture.

00:52:48.680 --> 00:52:52.850
And for me, one of my
aunts-- one of my uncles

00:52:52.850 --> 00:52:54.275
is married into [INAUDIBLE].

00:52:54.275 --> 00:52:57.036
A sister is married
into Karnataka.

00:52:57.036 --> 00:52:58.160
My wife is from Tamil Nadu.

00:53:00.950 --> 00:53:04.280
The other sister is
married into Sindh.

00:53:04.280 --> 00:53:08.920
So our home has been like--
my mother is from Maharashtra.

00:53:08.920 --> 00:53:11.830
My granny was from Maharashtra.

00:53:11.830 --> 00:53:12.840
And we are Gujaratis.

00:53:12.840 --> 00:53:15.510
So we were already having
six or seven languages

00:53:15.510 --> 00:53:18.670
within the family,
so it was fantastic.

00:53:18.670 --> 00:53:20.500
It was like learning at home.

00:53:20.500 --> 00:53:26.630
[NON-ENGLISH SPEECH] So it
was a natural inclination.

00:53:26.630 --> 00:53:29.840
So I love singing--
singing, per se.

00:53:29.840 --> 00:53:30.520
I love music.

00:53:30.520 --> 00:53:32.852
So language is not a problem.

00:53:32.852 --> 00:53:34.547
AUDIENCE: [NON-ENGLISH SPEECH]

00:53:34.547 --> 00:53:36.130
KUNAL GANJAWALA:
[NON ENGLISH SPEECH],

00:53:36.130 --> 00:53:37.089
thank you, yes.

00:53:37.089 --> 00:53:38.130
AUDIENCE: Talking to you.

00:53:38.130 --> 00:53:38.760
Thank you.

00:53:38.760 --> 00:53:39.884
KUNAL GANJAWALA: Thank you.

00:53:45.450 --> 00:53:47.730
I'd leave the
microphone now to you

00:53:47.730 --> 00:53:49.754
to speak to the other artists.

