00:56:50.020 --> 00:56:52.650
In this way you have
been a pioneering wave

00:56:52.650 --> 00:56:54.210
of fusion music.

00:56:54.210 --> 00:56:55.360
That's great.

00:56:55.360 --> 00:56:57.870
I would love to know, how
do you define fusion music,

00:56:57.870 --> 00:57:00.740
and what are your thoughts
in its growth in popularity

00:57:00.740 --> 00:57:02.450
over the past several decades?

00:57:02.450 --> 00:57:04.950
MANDOLIN U. RAJESH:
Well, life changes.

00:57:04.950 --> 00:57:06.930
Change is permanent.

00:57:06.930 --> 00:57:11.580
Fusion in music is-- there's
nothing called fusion music.

00:57:11.580 --> 00:57:14.746
It's just trying to--
it's like food, you know?

00:57:14.746 --> 00:57:17.535
You have cuisines,
multi cuisines.

00:57:17.535 --> 00:57:21.470
Now we have every cuisine
in our house cooking.

00:57:21.470 --> 00:57:24.320
We just have some fried rice.

00:57:24.320 --> 00:57:25.790
Likewise in music.

00:57:25.790 --> 00:57:29.400
It's nice to collaborate,
and it's basically conversing

00:57:29.400 --> 00:57:30.700
in a different language.

00:57:30.700 --> 00:57:33.840
Fusion is nothing but two
languages trying to talk,

00:57:33.840 --> 00:57:37.820
and we come to a point where we
get understanding the language.

00:57:37.820 --> 00:57:39.130
That's fusion music.

00:57:39.130 --> 00:57:40.670
VIKAS MARWAHA: That's true.

00:57:40.670 --> 00:57:44.610
So we all know your late
brother, U Srinivas,

00:57:44.610 --> 00:57:48.270
who was an undisputed
wizard on the mandolin.

00:57:48.270 --> 00:57:51.705
Can you share with us more about
his influence on your music?

00:57:51.705 --> 00:57:53.080
MANDOLIN U. RAJESH:
Of course, he

00:57:53.080 --> 00:57:55.730
is the person who
brought this instrument

00:57:55.730 --> 00:57:57.690
to the Indian classical music.

00:57:57.690 --> 00:58:02.390
He was the first person,
and he is everything

00:58:02.390 --> 00:58:03.912
for me-- inspiration.

00:58:03.912 --> 00:58:04.495
He is my guru.

00:58:04.495 --> 00:58:05.170
He's brother.

00:58:05.170 --> 00:58:08.010
He is my guiding
light, everything.

00:58:08.010 --> 00:58:11.530
And without him, I would have
not been a musician at all.

00:58:11.530 --> 00:58:13.740
I just wanted to become
a pilot, actually.

00:58:13.740 --> 00:58:19.040
So it's karma or accident
that incident just happened.

00:58:19.040 --> 00:58:22.110
And he's just a great blessing
to our Indian classical music,

00:58:22.110 --> 00:58:29.190
because what he did is--
Indian music has been there

00:58:29.190 --> 00:58:34.980
for thousands of years, but
he brought a new instrument,

00:58:34.980 --> 00:58:41.280
and then brought the old format
of music to the world again.

00:58:41.280 --> 00:58:45.180
And he made Western
people go, wow,

00:58:45.180 --> 00:58:48.470
because mandolin is more
a romantic instrument,

00:58:48.470 --> 00:58:49.740
plays more of harmony.

00:58:49.740 --> 00:58:53.400
And he adapted it
and modified it

00:58:53.400 --> 00:58:55.690
to play the mainstream
Indian classical music, which

00:58:55.690 --> 00:58:59.299
is very difficult. There's a
lot of long notes, long slide

00:58:59.299 --> 00:59:00.090
notes, [INAUDIBLE].

00:59:03.110 --> 00:59:04.880
He's the person who
made the difference

00:59:04.880 --> 00:59:06.070
to Indian classical music.

00:59:06.070 --> 00:59:09.107
VIKAS MARWAHA: Did he used to
play mostly electric mandolin?

00:59:09.107 --> 00:59:09.690
Is that right?

00:59:09.690 --> 00:59:11.689
MANDOLIN U. RAJESH: He
started with an acoustic,

00:59:11.689 --> 00:59:15.630
then he realized that
Indian classical music needs

00:59:15.630 --> 00:59:20.630
more sustained notes, so he
added the element of pickup

00:59:20.630 --> 00:59:23.150
and made it more electric.

00:59:23.150 --> 00:59:26.670
VIKAS MARWAHA: I've been
following recently [INAUDIBLE].

00:59:26.670 --> 00:59:29.040
He plays electric
version of a sitar,

00:59:29.040 --> 00:59:35.060
so this is amazing, how you guys
are bringing the Indian music

00:59:35.060 --> 00:59:40.010
through instruments like these
with beautiful harmonies.

00:59:40.010 --> 00:59:43.940
So sir, how did your
training happen?

00:59:43.940 --> 00:59:47.040
Tell us more about how many
hours you put into training,

00:59:47.040 --> 00:59:50.250
and how did you used to train?

00:59:50.250 --> 00:59:52.000
MANDOLIN U. RAJESH:
Let me be very honest.

00:59:52.000 --> 00:59:54.515
I was not-- wanted
to be a musician.

00:59:54.515 --> 00:59:55.640
I wanted to become a pilot.

00:59:55.640 --> 00:59:59.210
And when I was six I
started learning it

00:59:59.210 --> 01:00:02.230
because my dad is a strict
dad and I have to learn it.

01:00:02.230 --> 01:00:05.760
If not, I'll get nicely whacked.

01:00:05.760 --> 01:00:09.480
But when I was 10
or 11 years old,

01:00:09.480 --> 01:00:12.240
I met this great saint Indian.

01:00:12.240 --> 01:00:16.430
He lived for 100
years, [INAUDIBLE].

01:00:16.430 --> 01:00:20.850
And he said no
piloting, only music.

01:00:20.850 --> 01:00:24.490
Because they don't talk
much, very few words.

01:00:24.490 --> 01:00:29.330
And that was the day I performed
first, like my brother.

01:00:29.330 --> 01:00:32.530
And my life's
changed from there.

01:00:32.530 --> 01:00:34.870
It all started like that.

01:00:34.870 --> 01:00:36.210
VIKAS MARWAHA: That's so great.

